{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.34,0.07,0.24,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/596"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3384"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman with a background of severe diabetic nephropathy presents to the emergency department after a recent bout of gastroenteritis with severe diarrhoea, vomiting, and intolerance of oral food and fluid. She complains of ongoing nausea, anorexia, fatigue, muscle cramps, pruritis, and a recent onset of pleuritic central chest pain which worsens on lying down.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 142/86 mmHg, pulse 98/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 22/min. There is a rub audible at the left sternal border.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn arterial blood gas on room air shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.24 [7.35 - 7.45]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 74 [80 - 100]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 36 [35 - 45]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 13 [22 - 26]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa 139 [135 - 145]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK 6.0 [3.6 - 5.2]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl 106 [95 - 110]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to have contributed to the acid-base disturbance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute pulmonary oedema","Diarrhoea and vomiting","Hyperkalaemia","Renal tubular acidosis","Uraemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anion gap is in this case is\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa + K - Cl - HCO3\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E= 139 + 6 - 106 - 13\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E= 26 (refernce range 8 - 16 mmol - provided K included)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnion gap is often calculated ignoring potassium given its comparatively small contribution, however in cases of hyperkalaemia, it may be sensible to include it in the calculation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the arterial blood gas picture shows a high anion gap metabolic acidosis (HAGMA) with partial respiratory compensation. Of the causes listed, only \u003Cstrong\u003Euraemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a HAGMA. The patient appears to be suffering from uraemic syndrome given her symptoms and evidence of pericarditis, likely due to an acute worsening of her severe kidney disease secondary to dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pulmonary oedema\u003C/strong\u003E typically does not affect acid-base homeostasis unless it is severe enough to cause hypercapnia, at which point one would also expect more profound hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiarrhoea and vomiting\u003C/strong\u003E would not account for this picture - diarrhoea by itself typically causes a normal anion gap acidosis due to the GI loss of bicarbonate, and vomiting causes a metabolic alkalosis due to loss of hydrogen ions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a common feature of severe kidney failure. While severe acidaemia can cause or exacerbate hyperkalaemia, the reverse is not true and potassium exerts a negligible effect on acid-base homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal tubular acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic cause of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Differentiating between a high and normal anion gap metabolic acidosis allows determination of the likely underlying cause."],"references":["Zemaitis MR, Foris LA, Katta S, et al. Uremia. [Updated 2020 Aug 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441859/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:31:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:31:59+09:30"},"relati